# Overview / Exec Summary

This paper will explore how an AI agent might be constructed to provide information on FinOps the practice using access to content available to the FinOps Foundation. 

It should include:

- Use cases desired by end users (by type of user)  
- Description of data sources available to the agent  
- Use and access restrictions for each source  
- Potential architectures for delivering on use cases  
- Estimate of cost and overall build recommendations

Open questions:

- [ ] Quality of input to provide consistently correct output  
- [ ] How to put the corpus together  
- [ ] Product based, will need support  
- [ ] Load user context into questions to respond appropriately  
- [ ] What are the current searches, looks, stays  
- [ ] May not be the quantity of content to justify the cost to build/maintain  
- [ ] Ability to do live lookups may make a model training less necessary  
- [ ] Would this be available to the general public?  
- 

The base architecture would be a Retrieval Augmented Generation (RAG) solution. The resources would be aggregated into a storage location so the RAG data could be indexed and stored for reference during chat bot interactions. If the data didn’t change often we could consider fine tuning a model but this would not be ideal to support for the long term as we’d need to re fine tune it every time the data changed in a meaningful way. With RAG we don’t need to do this, we can just re-index and update the vector DB. Vector DB’s can be somewhat expensive depending on the DB used. Much more than the token processing. Some solutions like AWS S3 Vectors are a low cost alternative (90% savings) though they are slower. 

Automation, ideally we’d want to automate as much of the data ingestion as possible. Website scrape, Slack ingestion, Transcripts etc to avoid manual effort. Some platforms allow website scraping automatically but other data ingestion sources would need to be evaluated.

We also want to define the guardrails for the automation above to filter out the sensitive and confidential information from the data sources. Setting this up would be extremely important.

- Depending on the source and the requester  
- Would be very valuable to differentiate the answers based on the requester, and include certain sources or limit answer types based on that

On Guardrails: Bedrock does a great job helping setting up all sorts of guardrails (PII, unauthorized actions, word filters, sensitive topics…). 

With Bedrock you can also do contextual grounding, which will be very important for the chatbot not to come with fake quotes or totally made up recomandations.

Regarding the chatbot UI, we can use chainlit on an EC2 instance, but it needs to scale well for multi-concurrency. Gradio can be an option as well, if it can scale. Or Meso.

RAG: Bedrock Knowledge Bases could be very handy, and we can connect to the S3 vector store during the knowledge base creation

List of Questions that need to be answered:

What would be a planned roadmap for a product like this?

1. Source data identification (All that can go to the chat ), foundation open source material, youtube videos content, pdfs, presentations, whitepapers etc

# Body Section

## Description

What chatbot IS:

* Conversational AI that can talk with users about FinOps  
* It gives information about theoretical aspects of FinOps, pointers to the sources, general ideas on various aspects of FinOps practice  
* It covers FinOps topics better than the major LLMs by OpenAI, Anthropic, etc.

What chatbot IS NOT:

* An all-in AI FinOps tool that has access to user’s cloud environments, cost data, etc. and that is capable of providing concrete optimization advice/action

## Architecture

This architecture could be implemented in AWS, with the chatbot interface running on an EC2 instance, the agent is running on EC2 and interrogating LLM through Bedrock. The solution can leverage MCPs, or not. It will leverage RAG with Bedrock Knowledge Base, and corpus in S3 Vector; Use Titan and Opensearch serverless for the embeddings. Guardrails and grounding to be implemented with Bedrock.

## Sources

THe main purpose of the chatbot is to provide the information on the FinOps practice that is:

* More accurate that the output of common LLMs  
* More up-to-date than the output of common LLMs  
* Has concrete cases and examples from the FinOps community

To achieve this differentiated state, we need to have acces to the following data sources:

1. FinOps Foundation sources (main differentiator)  
   1. Slack conversations from certain channels (like FinOps job board, WG channels, etc). List of channels:  
      1. \#events  
      2. \#jobs  
      3. …  
   2. Transcripts/videos of F2 meetings  
      1. Monthly events  
      2. WG calls  
      3. Selected internal meetings (?)  
      4. …  
   3. Published materials by F2 Foundation  
      1. [finops.org](http://finops.org)  
      2. YouTube channel  
      3. …  
2. Vendor sources  
   1. Each vendor provides a set of materials to be shared and is responsible for keeping them updated (?)  
   2. …  
3. Cloud provider sources  
   1. Documentation (MCP?)  
   2. Custom data provided by cloud providers (?)

## Testing, Guardrails and evals

It is very important to define guardrails for this project, as the data sources that make it differentiated from the mainstream LLMs also make it vulnerable to the privacy leaks.

LangSmith or LangFuze can be used for evals.
